# Join is used to combine two or more datasets/data frames. Appropriate join type in required for specific workflow. 
    # There are several types of join in R language. 
    # Joins based on their task is considered mutating joins and filtering joins. 
# Most common 4 joins(mutating) are: inner_join, left_join, right_join, full_join. 

# Filtering joins: Filtering join keep or removes obvervations from the first table. 
# Does not add new variables. 
# It is more like subtracting set from another set. 
# Filtering verbs are: semi_join and anti_join.
    # semi_join and anti_join both provides the column and data from first table that exists (semi) or not exist(anti) in other table. 

# Difference between mutating verbs and filtering verbs in join: 
     # Mutating verbs matches observations and provide variables/column from both datasets. 
     # Filtering verbs provides only existing variables in first dataset and provide matches or no matches data.

 # inner_join: joins only the matching data from both datasets. 
 #   dataset_1 %>% 
        inner_join(dataset_2, by= "matching column name", suffix= c("_dataset1", "_dataset2"))
 #   dataset_1 %>% 
        inner_join(dataset_2, by= c("match column from 1" = "match column from 2") ) 
 # Join can be done over multiple columns. In that case, use comma inside by (do not use equal). 



